<article>
    <h1>Wagyu Beef Ren&#xAD;dang ($32, above)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210103/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-03"><time>2021-01-03</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This ex­cel­lent ren­dang works not just be­cause it is cooked with Westholme wagyu from Aus­tralia, but also be­cause of the cut cho­sen.</p>
    <p>The beef ribs used boast dif­fer­ent tex­tures af­ter hours of sim­mer­ing – rang­ing from ten­der meat that has fallen off the bone to car­ti­lage that turns into melt-in-the-mouth gelatin. That is some­thing you will not get from a lean cut like round or flank.</p>
    <p>The high-fat con­tent also means that as it melts in the heat, the blended spices are fried in tasty tal­low to a fra­grant paste. This is left to caramelise gently be­fore shred­ded co­conut is added to thicken it.</p>
    <p>Un­like typ­i­cal Sin­ga­pore ren­dang which comes with gravy, this has hardly any liq­uid. The re­sult is a more in­tense aroma and I am quite happy there is not much chilli heat to dis­tract from how de­li­cious it is.</p>

